If you have "all the tools in the world" and want to eliminate the ACI cold-start while supporting multiple users, the professional choice is Azure Container Apps (ACA) with a Dedicated Browser Pool (or a self-hosted Browserless instance).

This architecture moves you from a "start-stop" model to a "persistent-but-isolated" model.

1. The "Gold Standard" Architecture
   Instead of one container per user, use Azure Container Apps to host a "Browser Cluster."

Compute: Azure Container Apps (ACA).

The "Secret Sauce": Use the Browserless.io Open Source Docker Image.

Isolation: Use Playwright Browser Contexts to keep users separate.

VNC: Browserless comes with a built-in "Live View" (debugger) that gives you a URL for the UI without you having to configure Xvfb or x11vnc manually.

2. Why this is the winning move:
   Instant Warm Start: Keep a minReplica: 1 in ACA. The container is always running, but you only pay for the idle CPU. When a user hits "Sync," the response is sub-second.

Native Multi-User Support: One Browserless container can handle 10+ concurrent users (depending on RAM). You don't need to spin up new infra for User #2; you just spawn a new BrowserContext.

Automatic Scaling: If 50 people click "Sync" at once, ACA uses KEDA to automatically spin up more container replicas to handle the load.

Caddy Simplified: Caddy sits in front of the ACA Environment. It handles your domain and SSL, then sends traffic to the Browserless WebSocket port.

3. Implementation Roadmap
   Step 1: Deploy Browserless to ACA
   Use the browserless/chrome image. Set the environment variable CONCURRENT_SESSIONS=10 to limit how many browsers run in one container.

Step 2: The "Hybrid" Sync Script
Your backend no longer calls beginStart(). Instead, it sends the user's userId to your script, which connects to the warm cluster:

JavaScript
// Connect to your ALWAYS-ON container via Caddy/ACA
const browser = await chromium.connect(`wss://your-caddy-domain.com/playwright?token=YOUR_API_TOKEN`);

// Create a totally isolated session (Incognito)
const context = await browser.newContext();
const page = await context.newPage();

// Do the logic...
await page.goto("https://facebook.com/login");
// ...
Step 3: Handling the "Human in the Loop"
Since Browserless has a built-in UI, you can get a "Session Recording" or "Live Debug" URL programmatically. When your script detects a login is needed, it sends that Browserless Live URL to your webapp. The user clicks it, logs in through the Browserless proxy, and the script continues automatically.

