To answer your question directly: The stream is surprisingly good—often better and lower latency than noVNC—because it uses a direct binary screencast over a WebSocket.

While noVNC transmits a full "Desktop" (including the OS, taskbars, and windows), Browserless streams only the browser viewport. This significantly reduces the amount of data being sent.

1. How the Stream Works (The "Live URL")
   In Browserless, this feature is called the Live Debugger or LiveView.

Performance: It typically runs at 15–30 FPS. For a login screen, this feels "smooth." You won't notice much lag when typing or clicking.

Latency: Since it bypasses the heavy Xvfb/VNC stack and streams frames directly from the Chrome DevTools Protocol (CDP), the input lag is usually under 100–200ms.

Quality: You can actually configure the stream quality in your connection string:

&quality=70&type=jpeg (Standard)

&quality=95 (Crystal clear, but uses more bandwidth)

2. How to get the "Link"
   You don't have to build a UI for this. When you use the Browserless Docker image, it provides a built-in session viewer.

Step 1: Connect with a "Tracking ID"
In your Playwright code, you add a custom ID to the connection string:

JavaScript
const browser = await chromium.connectOverCDP(
`wss://your-browserless-domain.com/playwright?trackingId=${userId}`
);
Step 2: Generate the User's Link
You can then give the user a URL that points directly to that specific running session. If you are self-hosting, the URL structure usually looks like this:
https://your-browserless-domain.com/debugger?id={userId}

3. Why this is the "Pro" Move
   No Sidecars: You can delete your VNC and noVNC containers. Browserless handles the "seeing the browser" part natively.

Shareable: You can send this link to a user, and it just works in their browser with no extra software.

Stealth: Since the browser is "always on" and just spawning new contexts, Facebook is less likely to flag the session than it is when a brand-new ACI container boots up from a fresh IP every time.

