To move from your slow ACI setup to a "Warm" Browserless architecture, follow these exact steps. This setup will give you sub-second browser starts and a smooth "Live View" for the user login.

1. Deploy the Browserless Service
   You can run this on Azure Container Apps (ACA) or even a small VM. Use the following configuration:

Image: ghcr.io/browserless/chromium

Environment Variables:

CONCURRENT=10 (Allows 10 users to sync at once in one container)

TOKEN=your_secure_password (Protects your browser from unauthorized use)

TIMEOUT=300000 (5-minute idle timeout to prevent zombie browsers)

2. Update your Caddyfile
   Your Caddy sidecar needs to proxy both the WebSocket (for Playwright) and the HTTP (for the Live View).

Code snippet
your-sync-domain.com { # Reverse proxy to the Browserless container on port 3000
reverse_proxy localhost:3000 {
header_up Host {host}
header_up X-Real-IP {remote_host}
}
} 3. Update the Playwright Connection
You no longer "launch" a browser; you connect to the warm one. Replace your launch logic with this:

JavaScript
// Connect to the warm cluster
const browser = await chromium.connectOverCDP(
`wss://your-sync-domain.com/chromium/playwright?token=your_secure_password&trackingId=${userId}`
);

// Get the existing default context or create one
const context = await browser.newContext();
const page = await context.newPage(); 4. Direct the User to the "Live View"
When your script detects that a login is required (using your isLoggedIn check), send this URL to your frontend. The user can open it in a new tab to see the browser and log in.

The Live View URL:
https://your-sync-domain.com/debugger/?token=your_secure_password&id=${userId}

Pro Tip: Because you are using a trackingId in the connection string, Browserless automatically isolates that session's view to that specific ID.

5. Summary of the New Workflow
   User clicks Sync: Your backend instantly calls the Playwright script.

Playwright Connects: It takes < 500ms to connect to the warm Browserless instance.

Auth Check: Script goes to /login. If failed, it sends the Debugger URL to the user.

User Logs In: User sees a smooth 30fps stream of the browser, types their credentials, and finishes.

Script Resumes: As soon as isLoggedIn returns true, the script continues to Marketplace and captures the session.

Cleanup: await context.close() wipes the session from the container's RAM, keeping it fresh for the next user.
